snippet.textDisplay: Trevor Noah brings up a serious, valid point - ie: Fake News - it's not just a US phenomena ! ... Sure, not everything they publish is "fake",  but it is easy enough to see the Establishment bias built into more and more articles, and media "angles" on everyday news.  In Britain, or the US, it is so clear these days to see who is "owned" by who, whether Conservative, Democrat, Anarchyst, or Libertarian.  And they distort stories to please some political group or commercial alliance (like an Advertiser).  It is rife - it is corrupt - it "steals" democracy from the working class.  They are saying there is more honest news on show's like Trevor's, or Stephen's, or the two Jimmy's (and of course Oliver).  I also think we get 99% truth out of all the young, internet news sources that have opened up (one example, TYT).  I think we are on a precipice, but the nightly  comedians and the "new" I-news outlets will help us make the right choices. (end of soapbox).

snippet.textDisplay:
The sad truth is that some still believe that people of colour should ‘know their place in society’. This is embodied in the term ‘uppity n***a’ which was used by white southerners in the US to describe a black person who they believed ‘thought highly of themselves.’ Which obviously was and still is an uncomfortable thought for some white people. The point is that there is still a deep and perhaps subconscious aversion by white people to have a person of colour ‘preach’ or ‘dictate’ to them or for a black person to seemingly view themselves as being the same or higher position. These are facts.

It’s true that not all negative coverage of MM was racist but it would be completely naive and irresponsible to state that there has been no racism at all in the media and social media commentary.

Even if it’s one racist article out of 100, the racism must be singled out, condemned and discussed publicly. It’s the responsibility of all of us in society to build the type of environment that protects and uplifts all citizens.

As much as MM has a duty to the crown and royal family, she - more importantly - has a duty to people of colour that are looking up to her for representation to stand up against destructive prejudice and undertones. And we should support her.

This woman was not born with a silver spoon. There is no way she could have prepared for this. And when you look at everything objectively; why do you really hate her? What has she done that would warrant this persistent negativity and hate? It’s unjustifiable.

The point is that there is still a deep and perhaps subconscious aversion by white people to have a person of colour ‘preach’ or ‘dictate’ to them or for a black person to seemingly view themselves as being the same or higher position.
